<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-235-220  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 235 220.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  March 1990 v13 n3 p33(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The market at large: proprietary systems wane as computer graphicsblends with mainstream computing. (Graphics Industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gantz, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer graphics industry is forecasted to more than doublefrom a $26.3 billion market in 1989 to almost $50 billion in 1993,with proprietary systems shrinking in importance from aboutone-half of the market to less than one-third.andP;  The growth will bein general purpose systems, commercial graphic applications andconvenience computer graphics.andP;  During the 1980s, changes thathave led to the ten-fold growth in the computer graphics industryincluded new hardware and software for electronic and desktoppublishing, medical imaging technology, computer aided design,computer animation, laser printers, color monitors and Apple'sMacintosh.andP;  Growth is expected in applications for designengineering, architecture, visualization, HDTV, graphic arts,mapping, science and medicine.andP;  This predicted growth may behindered by weakness in software development and a lack ofstandards.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer GraphicsIndustry AnalysisForecastingMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Worldwide market for computer graphics from US vendors, 1989 to1993 (graph)Changes in number of proprietary, dedicated and general purposesystems (graph)US suppliers' major markets, 1993: CAD-CAE, graphic arts,science-medicine (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>